summaries.full: In the six years since Real Sports profiled Camp Abilities, this revolutionary sports camp for blind and visually impaired children has grown a great deal--much like the kids we met there.

titles.short: Sex Abuse at University of Michigan
titles.full: Sex Abuse at University of Michigan

summaries.short: More than a thousand athletes at the Univ. of Michigan have accused a former doctor of decades of sexual assault dating back to the 1960s.
summaries.full: More than a thousand collegiate athletes at the University of Michigan have accused a former doctor at the athletic department, Robert Anderson, of sexual assault dating as far back as the 1960s, making it perhaps the largest case of sexual abuse in college sports history. Despite more than a dozen reports to Michigan coaches and staff, the abuse is only now coming to light.

summaries.short: In an effort to battle Montana’s alarming suicide rate, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament has built over two dozen skateparks.
summaries.full: In an effort to battle Montana’s alarming suicide rate, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament has built over two dozen skateparks, looking to bring kids together and fight the loneliness and isolation that he once felt.

summaries.short: Former NBA All-Star Amar’e Stoudemire has spent the last decade on a spiritual journey, and now leads a devout Jewish life.
summaries.full: Once one of the NBA’s top attractions, former All-Star Amar’e Stoudemire has spent the last decade on a spiritual journey, and now leads a devout Jewish life. Having completed a conversion to Modern Orthodoxy while living in Israel, Real Sports take a peek inside Stoudemire’s new faith, life, and identity.

summaries.short: LA Rams assistant coach Marcus Dixon almost never found his NFL dream due to being wrongfully imprisoned as a teen two decades ago.
summaries.full: Marcus Dixon of the LA Rams is one of nearly 500 assistant coaches in the NFL—a dream career for Dixon whose wrongful imprisonment as a teen two decades ago made finding such a job seem impossible.

summaries.short: Real Sports returns with its annual year-end special that looks back at the most interesting, compelling and important stories from 2021.
summaries.full: Real Sports returns with its annual year-end special that looks back at 2021 and recalls some of the most interesting, compelling and important stories it aired over the last twelve months. Featured stories include: DeMaurice Smith; sexual abuse at Michigan; NCAA Gold Rush; Mark Davis; Female Sports Reporters; Long Haulers; Wim Hof; and more.

summaries.short: Emerging from the shadow of his controversial dad, Raiders owner Mark Davis is ushering in a new era for the Silver and Black in Sin City.
summaries.full: Ten years after inheriting the Oakland Raiders from his controversial father, Al, Mark Davis has finally achieved what no one else has ever been able to do – bring the NFL to Las Vegas.

summaries.short: The U.S. Forest Service has a secret weapon: Jerry Garcia – a firefighter who happens to be one of the country’s top ultramarathon runners.
summaries.full: Amid another catastrophic fire season, the U.S. Forest Service has a secret weapon: Jerry Garcia – a firefighter who also happens to be one of the country’s top ultramarathon runners.

summaries.full: ESPN's ultimate insider Adam Schefter is still breaking more NFL news than anyone else in the game. But what few people know is Schefter's unlikely personal story involving his marriage to a 9/11 widow – one that mirrors "Real Sports" correspondent, Jon Frankel.

summaries.short: Segments: Ex-NBA stars turned marijuana moguls; hunting contests to control wildlife; 10 year-old chess prodigy; paragliding for disabled.
summaries.full: Segments: Former NBA stars jump into the cannabis biz aiming to grow profits and help the Black community; with various wildlife populations out of control, some hunters are competing for cash prizes to curb unwanted animals; ten-year-old Nigerian refugee Tani Adewumi is a rising star in the world of chess; a paragliding outfit gives people who can’t walk the chance to fly.

summaries.short: Former NBA stars are part of the new green gold rush of the legal cannabis industry, looking to grow profits and help the Black community.
summaries.full: Former NBA stars Al Harrington and Matt Barnes are part of the new green gold rush of the legal cannabis industry, looking to grow profits and help build investment and ownership opportunities in the Black community.

summaries.short: With various wildlife populations out of control across America, some hunters are now competing for cash prizes to curb unwanted animals.
summaries.full: With various animal populations growing out of control and causing damage across the country, hunting contests offering cash prizes have been organized to help curb unwanted wildlife. But in recent years, with pressure mounting from animal rights groups, some states have started banning these contests, while experts question their overall effectiveness.

summaries.short: Two years ago, 10 year-old Nigerian refugee Tani Adewumi lived in a homeless shelter. Today he is a rising star in the world of chess.
summaries.full: Tani Adewumi isn’t your typical ten-year-old. Instead of wanting to play in the NFL or NBA, he dreams about becoming the youngest player ever to become a Grand Master in chess. It would be a remarkable achievement, considering just two years ago, Tani and his family were living in a New York City homeless shelter after fleeing Boko Haram in their native Nigeria.

summaries.short: Project Airtime gives disabled athletes the chance to fly - offering them joy, exhilaration, and the opportunity to feel whole again.
summaries.full: In 2018, we first discovered Utah-based Project Airtime, an adaptive paragliding outfit founded by one-time extreme sportsman Chris Santacrocce. Disabled athlete Joe Stone has now brought Santacrocce’s mission to Jackson, Wy., where he’s established a Project Airtime outpost to spread the paragliding gospel and give others like him the chance to feel whole again.

summaries.full: Host Max Gershberg is joined by sports super agent Leigh Steinberg, who went from living the high life to falling into bankruptcy and battling addiction to then rebuilding his life and returning to prominence as a top agent. Steinberg reflects on his journey from when Real Sports last spoke with him in 2012.
